Morning light spilled across unfinished canvases. She hadn't captured it right—the precise blue of that evening they shared wine above the Seine. Each attempt darkened with longing. Pigment couldn't hold memory; it slipped through brush bristles like time through fingers. The ache of almost—almost perfect, almost love—seeped into every color she mixed.

