Her miniskirt swayed in perfect time as the Wurlitzer spilled Dusty Springfield across checkerboard tiles. Cherry-red boots and matching headband—she was a pop art dream come to life. College boys paused mid-burger, watching her drop a dime for another play. She knew better than to waste wishes on stars; she saved them for B-7 on jukeboxes, where dreams had a three-minute guarantee.

